{
  "answer": "**Freedom of thought (Denkfreiheit).**\n\nIn *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens* (1793), Johann Gottlieb Fichte argues that freedom of thought is an essential, inalienable human right rooted in personhood, morality, and the divine spark of conscience, distinguishing humans from animals and enabling free willing and rational self-activity.[^1] Princes derive their authority solely from a social contract transferring alienable rights to external actions for protection, but they possess no such rights over inalienable ones like freedom of thought, which individuals cannot alienate even if they wished to do so.[^2] Princes falsely claim to \"grant\" permission to think freely (which they cannot, as it is not theirs to give) while attempting to suppress its communication; Fichte insists they have \"no right to suppress our freedom of thought,\" as doing so would violate natural rights that princes must protect rather than undermine.[^3][^4]\n\n[^1]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, ch.2 [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-e62dae).\n\n[^2]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, ch.2 [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-8e054b).\n\n[^3]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, ch.2 [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-44e1de).\n\n[^4]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, ch.2 [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-b0279a).",
